                       **** MY RECOMMENDATIONS ****

 Plenty of people have asked me what do you really need for module ripping,
what are the best tools and what are the ones you use? Well this little
chapter should cover the main questions I hope but these can always vary
depending upon your machine, versions etc. but I will try to point out a
clear direction for beginners to head in.
 The best tools for hunting modules has to be by far the ExoticRipper. To
this date there is ExoticRipper V3.0 which has a GUI which makes it a lot
easier to use but as usual it is a bigger file and so has a higher chance
to write over the module on loading but it comes with the bog standard
version which can be better depending on how you are ripping the module. Of
course you can use the chipmem copy if the ripper is wiping over the module
on execution though!
 The other tool is MultiRipper, the last version I think I had was V3.1/2 I
am not sure but the last official release I can remember of was V3.0. This
was the best ripper in it's time and it still is in a way but this is only
because it has the ability to scan for decrunch headers on dos and non-dos
disks. The other problem I disliked about this program was that it was
extremly large for what it had to offer - EXTREMLY! Out if the two I would
choose the ExoticRipper but if possible get the two just in case.
 The other tools I recommend to get is a good disassembler, these range
from the bog standard MON programs to the MultiMON and others of similar
sorts. For the ultimate disassembler I do recommend ReSource and is worth
the money thats being charged for it. For loading, disassembling disk 
blocks etc. then a MON type program is very handy as they are quick and
easy to use. ReSource has this option but it is a little rough I think and
I only tend to use it for disassembling only files.
 A decent module replayer is a good idea with plenty of replayers as well.
I have DeliTracker and EaglePlayer, the reason for both of them is that
some of the replayers I have will only run on one of them and not the
other. At the moment I have around 130 replayers in total for different
types of modules and I am still looking for more or even updates of the
ones I already posses (HINT!).
 Those are the main things that I recommend for you to get but if possible
get an Action Replay, software or hardware. With this it can save you
plenty of time (extremly badly!) so you can do other things, if the reasons
are not obvious enough then ...... your a sad fucker!
 The last thing that I can think of getting for module ripping is a program
to convert ProTracker clones back to tracker again. In the old days it was
pretty easy to convert them back yourself because they were not so complex
but these days it can get very complex - ARRGHH! Anyway if you can lay your
hands on ProWizard V2.** or Perverter V1.44+ then grab them straight away
without a doubt as these are brilliant tools that really do save time and
energy. ProWizard is the best out of the two because it has plenty more
module type's that can be reconverted back to Tracker and does it a lot
better. I have found a few bugs in Perverter that fuck the converting
really badly in some cases and I suspect this is because of some rough and
quick coding but apart from that it is a nice program.
 That is about all I can think of, but of course if new versions come out
or new tools that are of use to me or I believe you then I will state them
in future updates of this ripping tutorial. Until then read the rest of the
file and happy ripping!

